\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {title}{The Role of Water in the Superconductivity of Sodium Cobaltate}{1}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {abstract}{Abstract}{1}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {I}Introduction}{1}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces The mechanism in one picture. When the gallery between the {CoO$_2$} sheets is narrow (left), the sodium sits at the centre of a single stiff well and the electrons stay bound to the oxygen: no gas, no soft mode, no pairing. Open the gallery past a critical spacing (right) and both change at once---charge spills back into the gallery as a two-dimensional electron gas, and the sodium well splits into a shallow double well in which the ion rattles. The gas carries and the rattle glues. Superconductivity lives in the narrow window between these two states and the polaronic state past it.}}{1}{}}
\newlabel{fig:schematic}{{1}{1}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {II}What happens when the gallery opens}{1}{}}
\newlabel{sec:opening}{{II}{1}{}{}{}}
\citation{RadhaLambrecht2021}
\newlabel{eq:landau}{{1}{2}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces The single-to-double-well transition. Energy $E(\delta )$ of the off-centre sodium displacement, computed for {Na$\,1\times 1$} (top, $x=1$) and {Na$\,\sqrt  {3}\times \sqrt  {3}$} (bottom, $x=1/3$) at the four gallery spacings; points are total energies, curves are the fits of Eq.~\eqref  {eq:landau} continued to sixth order where needed. At $5.5$~\r A{} the well is single and stiff ($\alpha >0$); by $6.9$~\r A{} it has split into a double well ($\alpha <0$) with minima marked. Open symbols with arrows ($c\geq 8.4$~\r A) flag scans that are still falling at the largest sampled displacement---there the sodium is adsorbing onto one layer and the quoted depth is only a lower bound.}}{2}{}}
\newlabel{fig:wells}{{2}{2}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {III}The pairing window}{2}{}}
\newlabel{sec:model}{{III}{2}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces The central result, three signatures of one transition against the {CoO$_2$}--{CoO$_2$} spacing $c$. (a)~The {Landau} coefficient $\alpha (c)$ for the three series; it crosses zero near $c^{\ast }_{\mathrm  {Na}}\approx 6.40$~\r A, where the single well becomes a double well. (b)~The Fermi-level density of states $N(0)$, which jumps from essentially zero to of order one state per {eV} at the same spacing---the interlayer electron gas switching on. (c)~The Allen--Dynes superconducting temperature: a narrow dome pinned just above $c^{\ast }$, with the shaded band spanning the electron--phonon coupling ansatz ($11$--$23$~K) and the thin vertical line at the $\lambda =2$ crossing marking the polaron wall---everywhere to its right the coupling exceeds the polaron limit and superconductivity is killed. The inset magnifies the narrow dome. The experimental anchors are the thin dashed verticals at $5.5$, $6.9$ and $9.9$~\r A: the dry parent and monolayer hydrate (not superconducting) fall on the walls, and the bilayer hydrate (star, $T_c=4.5$~K) does not sit in the static window---the difficulty of Sec.~\ref {sec:difficulty}, resolved there by water re-binding the sodium.}}{3}{}}
\newlabel{fig:money}{{3}{3}{}{}{}}
