\citation{Jalarvo2008}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces The rigid-cage water demonstration. (a)~Total energy $E(\delta )$ of the off-centre sodium at $c=9.9$~\r A{} in the $\sqrt  {3}\times \sqrt  {3}$ ($x=1/3$) cell, with a rigid four-{H$_2$O} solvation cage (hydrate) and with the water deleted (vacuum); points are {QE} total energies, curves guide the eye. Without water the curve runs away monotonically---the sodium chemisorbs onto a {CoO$_2$} sheet, an unstable ($V''(0)<0$) mode with no bound state. With the rigid cage it becomes a bound double well (minima $\approx \pm 0.30$~\r A, central barrier $\approx 0.20$~eV), a real confined mode of $\hbar \omega _{\mathrm  {eff}}\approx 23$~meV. The frozen cage re-binds the sodium but leaves the well deep; softening it into the pairing window is the work of the water's motion (text). (b)~The hydrate cell, drawn from the actual input coordinates (Appendix~\ref {app:water}), viewed along $c$: {CoO$_2$} sheets at top and bottom, the sodium on its plane at $c/2$, and the two-layer water cage between.}}{5}{}}
\newlabel{fig:water}{{5}{5}{}{}{}}
